IRS990.MissionDesc: Advocate for professional management of public lands.
IRS990.Desc: Advocated for effective mangement of 245 million acres of public land administered by BLM for the public's benefit and enjoyment. Produced quarterly issues of newsletter "The Public Lands Monitor" with a distribution to about 1000 recipients. PLF and BLM renewed our Memorandum of Understanding (MOU). PLF then hosted two receptions on behalf of BLM. PLF is also partnering with BLM on a History Project which will involve digitizing vital records. Provided testimony on BLM's 2023 appropriations to the House Appropriations Subcommittee and Senate Subcommittee on the Interior.

ProgSrvcAccomActy2Grp.Desc: Educated members on land issues and provided information and books to members on related issues. Held annual convention for members to network and share views on BLM issues. This year's theme was e-bike use.

ProgSrvcAccomActy3Grp.Desc: Awarded two $5,000 scholarships to college students earning degrees in pubic land managment or related fields. Neither student had any relationship to PLF Board Members or organization members.

ProgSrvcAccomActyOtherGrp.Desc: We held the 5th Biennial Student Congress. The students spent a week on the Boise State Campus discussing Wildland Fire, its implications for local communities and next steps for the BLM and USFS to take in addressing the issue. This years theme attracted the most applicants ever for the 25 spots.

SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: The Foundation has adopted the accounting of uncertainty in income taxes as required by the Income Taxes Topic (Topic 740) of the FASB Accounting Standards Codification. Topic 740 requires the Foundation to determine whether a tax position is more likely than not to be sustained upon examination by the applicable taxing authority, including resolution of any related appeals or litigation processes, based on the techincal merits of the position. The tax benefit to be recognized is measured as the largest amount of benefit that is more than fifty percent likely of being realized upon ultimate settlement, which could result in the Foundation recording a tax liability that would reduce the Foundation's net assets. Managemtn has analyzed the Foundation's tax positions, and has concluded that no liability for unrecognized tax benefits should be recorded related to uncertain tax positions taken on returns filied for open tax years 2018, 2019, 2020 and 2021, or expected to be taken in its 2022 tax return. The Foundation is not aware of any tax positions for which it believes that there is a resonable possibility that the total amounts of unrecognized tax benefits will change materially in the next twelve months.
Membership is available to any person supportive of the mission of the Public Lands Foundation. There is annual membership or life time membership options.

The board of directors is elected by the membership. A mailing is sent to all members with the list of candidates for them to choose from. The results are tabulated and the board of directors is formed.
The draft 990 is prepared and the Treasurer reviews. All changes are incorporated into the final return.
Upon request, the governing documents and financial statements are sent to inquirers.

Members volunteer to support National Public Lands Day events in many locations across the United States. These volunteers serve in various roles as needed. Additional members volunteer with numerous "Friends" organizations in support of public lands managed by the Bureau of Land Management.
